lass=title>   Re: Advise for Grouping... (Told like a Drill Instructor) Pi</span><hr size=1> /agree dalninil<br><br>especially in the mid 20s to low 30, groups often fight mobs that do more damage to them than they can handle, usually because their gear isn't up to par yet. a good example of this is split paw dungeon.<br><br>you can heal til you're oom, or you can stun a couple times.<br><br>or you can nuke the piss outta that caster mob and drop it like a bad habit.<br><br>it's entirely situational. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ualyissa.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Alyissa</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/22/02 3:13:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=402.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Advise for Grouping... (Told like a Drill Instructor) Pi</span><hr size=1> Yes, the main assist will already know which mob to attack next because the enchanter has already told them! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br><br>What I mean is, even if the main assist knows all the monsters in the area, they do not always know what the enchanter is doing.  While it may USUALLY be the best idea to attack Random_mob_04 next, the enchanter may tell you to attack Random_mob_03 instead, because 03 for whatever reasons, just happens to be resisting EVERYTHING the enchanter throws at it.<br><br>Normally, the main assist goes to 04, but in this case, it's a bad idea.  It will mean two mobs instead of one.<br><br>[Edit] - Had a half-finished paragraph in here I forgot to delete after I decided to not use it.  It made no sense just sitting here.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br><br>I did not mean that the enchanter is the above-all leader in a group, to shout out orders in every fight and dominate all other classes.  No, the enchanter being in charge is not a normal fight.  They should not be.  Crowd control skills are not needed when taking on a single mob.  But when the enchanter does give an order, it would be a good idea to follow it.  I do not mean to sound conceded, but in a massive fight, the enchanter's crowd controling skills are WAAAAAAY more important than melee damage.  Keeping the situation under control is the number ONE priority, and no one in the group can keep it under control better than the enchanter.  Not all fights follow the same basic patterns.  There are always variables, many of which the main assist will not be aware of right away.  Decisions need to be made yesterday, and unfortunatly, the main-assist might not know all the details until tomorrow.<br><br>An enchanter can give information such as 'Random_mob_03 resisting mez' and the group can decide what to do with the information, but that is a half-a-second of decision making that doesn't need to be made.  As in a real battle, excess thinking can get people killed.  There is no use to relay information to the group and then let the group decide if the enchanter can make the decision in the first place and shout a simple order.  It is pointless to say &quot;mob_04 mezzed&quot; then have the main-assist say decide to attack 03.  It wastes time, and that time could have been used to save the group.<br><br>An enchanter in charge is not normal and should not be normal, because an enchanter only needs take charge in an abnormal situation.  But even if in a basic, boring fight, your enchanter tells you for some reason to attack Mob 03 when common sense tells you to attack 04... the enchanter probably has a GOOD reason for telling you to do so, and does not have the time to type out what that reason is.  Perhaps they are going to charm something to take 2 mobs out of the immediate fight, perhaps they are going to mem-wipe a superior mob that would otherwise be attacked next, perhaps they simply made a mistake and mezzed the wrong mob.  But the enchanter knows the situation because they have the ability to control the situation.<br><br>Enchanter - &quot;Hey guys, I know you would normally attack Random_mob_06 next, but just so you know what I'm doing, I am going to mem-wipe it so it goes away and leaves us alone for good so we can focus on the 4 mobs that are going to break mez in about... oh, 7 seconds... so when you kill the mob you are on, I want you to all attack Random_mob_05 because it has been resisting my slow spells, and while you are doing that, I will re-mez the other 3 mobs.  When you are done with mob_05, I would like it if you all attacked Random_mob_03, because I will have JUST cast slow on that mob and it will be all ready for a beating.  I know you would have normally attacked 03, but I just want to be clear with you all so we all fully understand the situation and are able to effectivly deal with it.  Thank you for listening.&quot;<br><br>Enchanter, 5 seconds later - &quot;Hey, just so you guys know, the situation has changed.  In the time it took me to explain what I had been doing while you were all giving your full attention to killing the first mob, the 4 mezzed mobs broke mez and killed Fred the cleric rather quickly due to the fact that I could not re-mez them because I was busy explaining all my actions.  They are all now beating on my skull, and I am about 3 seconds from death. When I die, you guys will be on your own against 4 blue mobs and one red one.  GOOD LUCK!&quot;<br><br>How about this instead:<br><br>Enchanter - &quot;Attack 05 next&quot;<br><br>Not to sound like a moron elitest, but the enchanter owns the bad guys, and therefore owns the situation.  If you do not do what your enchanter says, you are creating a MAJOR problem.  You are working toward undoing all the enchanter's work.  You are helping the bad guys.  Not everyone plays the game the same.  What one may consider the primary threat, another may consider secondary.  But your enchanter is doing things to the other mobs while you are still fighting the first.  Because of this, it is the enchanter who must decide what is the primary threat, because he/she does not have time to wait for the main assist and pals to finish off the first mob and then decide what to attack next.  The enchanter does not have time to think &quot;who do I think the main-assist will attack next?&quot;  They have to make split-second decisions, and the rest of the group MUST to abide by those decisions or all will die.<br><br>Tanks are great.  I love tanks because they keep mobs off my sister.  But don't you DARE attack something she just told you to back off from.  &gt;=)<br><br>Again, I do not mean to come off as a freak saying that Enchanters are the best and all must bow before them and their orders.  Nor am I saying that all enchanters need to be Drill Instructors that scream at everyone and tell them what to do.  It's just that if you do not listen to the enchanter, you're hurting the group.<br><br>An enchanter need not give orders often, but when they do, those orders supersede ALL others.  Even your own common sense.<br><br>...unless your playing with that enchanter who is just no good.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    Then you should just lie down and die. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ualyissa.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Alyissa</A> at: 2/22/02 3:47:31 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/usteeltoefv.showPublicProfile?languag